response:
You need to find the value of $m$ such that
\begin{align*}
\frac{n!}{n - (m + 2)! (\text{factorial})} &= n - (m + 3)(\text{if }(m + 3) \leq n, (m + 3)! (\text{(factorial)}) \leq n \\
-\infty &\,\,\,\,\, \text{otherwise}
\end{align*}
The idea is to write $n!$ as a product of numbers, with $3$ as the smallest number (for example, if $n = 10, 10! = 90 \times 8 = 90 \times 8 \times 7$) and then keep factoring all the resulting factors (like factoring $720 = 36 \times 20 = 18 \times 10 \times 4$ for a higher count). The factors disappear when they are multiples of $3$, which will happen up to $n / 3$ times. <answer>That got me $n = 23$.

